-- PRESS DIGEST - -Hong Kong - March 27
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Wed Mar 26, 2014 09:54PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, March 27 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Thursday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Hong Kong should have a clear stance on regulating the bitcoin virtual currency and whether it should be taxed, financial analysts say. They were speaking after a decision by the United States Internal Revenue Service to treat virtual currency as property for tax purposes, instead of as currency. (http://link.reuters.com/muz87v) -- Americans who do not reveal their Hong Kong bank balances, earnings and property holdings to the US taxman face being branded "recalcitrants" after new rules come into force in the wake of an agreement signed with Washington this week. (http://link.reuters.com/nuz87v) -- China Life Insurance <601628.SS>, the mainland's largest insurer, hopes to secure better profit margins by boosting longer-term premium growth and improving sales channels amid an expected slowdown in the business. (http://link.reuters.com/puz87v)  THE STANDARD -- A warning that local interest rates may rise more sharply and sooner than expected, posing downward risk in the homes market, was sounded by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority. But Lui Che-woo, chairman of developer K Wah International <0173.HK> sees rates rising gradually. (http://link.reuters.com/ruz87v) -- A task force to speed up the importation of foreign workers for public infrastructure projects will be set up under the city's Development Bureau despite strong opposition to bringing in labour. (http://link.reuters.com/suz87v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Dah Sing Banking Group Ltd <2356.HK> said it planned to issue rights shares at HK$8 each to shareholders raising HK$1.2 billion ($154.67 million). HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- Five major Hong Kong developers, including Sun Hung Kai Properties <0016.HK>, Cheung Kong <0001.HK>, Henderson Land <0012.HK>, Sino Land <0083.HK> and New World Development <0017.HK>, are seen selling an aggregate 6,700 flats in the second quarter of 2014, double the volume from the previous quarter.